<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-104-486  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 104 486.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Jan 22 1990 v16 n2 p17(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The missing links in the fiber-optics market; equipment vendorseye high-growth market as a key standard emerges for fiber-optictelecom networks. (synchronous optic transmissions)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Davis, Dwight B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Emergence of synchronous optical transmission (Sonet) as a commonstandard for fiber-optic transmission is creating an emergingmarket among producers of telecommunication equipment.andP;  Publicnetwork carriers like the new standard because it offers ultrahighspeed and greater transmission capacity at lower costs because ofimproved economies of scale.andP;  Equipment vendors are hoping thatSonet will renew interest among corporations with privatenetworks.andP;  Sonet, which originated in the laboratories of BellCommunications Research, is still being designed.andP;  ANSI isintroducing the standard in phases: phase one came out in Mar1988, and phase two is expected in Feb 1990.andP;  An unexpected thirdphase may be necessary due to continuing difficulties in resolvingsome aspects of the standard.andP;  Several manufacturers, includingdominant AT and T Network Systems, already have phaseone-compatible products on the market.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SONET (Computer Network Protocol)TelecommunicationsCommunications IndustryStandardsFiber Optics.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   Sonet standard emerges. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>